  "prompt": "Why is cellphone called as cellphone?",
  "response": "A cellphone is called a cellphone because it is a telephone that uses cellular technology to connect to the network. The term \"cellular\" refers to the way the service area is divided into small hexagonal \"cells,\" each served by a base station. As a user moves from one cell to another, the call is automatically handed off to the new cell's base station, allowing for continuous communication. This technology was a significant advancement over earlier mobile phone systems, which had limited coverage and capacity. The term \"cellphone\" became popular in the 1980s as cellular technology became more widespread.",
